   1105          /***************************************************************************//**
   1106           * @brief
   1107           *   Enter energy mode 3 (EM3).
   1108           *
   1109           * @details
   1110           *   When entering EM3, the high-frequency clocks are disabled by hardware, i.e., HFXO,
   1111           *   HFRCO, and AUXHFRCO (for AUXHFRCO, see exception note below). In addition,
   1112           *   the low-frequency clocks, i.e., LFXO and LFRCO are disabled by software. When
   1113           *   re-entering EM0, HFRCO is re-enabled and the core will be clocked by the
   1114           *   configured HFRCO band. This ensures a quick wakeup from EM3.
   1115           *
   1116           *   However, prior to entering EM3, the core may have been using an
   1117           *   oscillator other than HFRCO. The @p restore parameter gives the user the option
   1118           *   to restore all HF/LF oscillators according to state prior to entering EM3,
   1119           *   as well as the clock used to clock the core. This restore procedure is
   1120           *   handled by software. However, since it is handled by software, it will not be restored
   1121           *   before completing the interrupt function(s) waking up the core!
   1122           *
   1123           * @note
   1124           *   If restoring core clock to use an oscillator other than HFRCO, this
   1125           *   function will stall until the oscillator has stabilized. Stalling time
   1126           *   can be reduced by adding interrupt support detecting stable oscillator,
   1127           *   and an asynchronous switch to the original oscillator. See CMU
   1128           *   documentation. This feature is, however, outside the scope of the
   1129           *   implementation in this function.
   1130           * @note
   1131           *   If ERRATA_FIX_EMU_E110_ENABLE is active, the core's SLEEPONEXIT feature
   1132           *   can't be used.
   1133           * @note
   1134           *   This function is incompatible with the Power Manager module. When the
   1135           *   Power Manager module is present, it must be the one deciding at which
   1136           *   EM level the device sleeps to ensure the application properly works. Using
   1137           *   both at the same time could lead to undefined behavior in the application.
   1138           * @par
   1139           *   If HFXO/LFXO/LFRCO are re-enabled by this function, and NOT used to clock
   1140           *   the core, this function will not wait for those oscillators to stabilize.
   1141           *   This must be considered by the application if trying to use features
   1142           *   relying on those oscillators upon return.
   1143           * @par
   1144           *   If a debugger is attached, the AUXHFRCO will not be disabled if enabled
   1145           *   upon entering EM3. It will, therefore, remain enabled when returning to EM0
   1146           *   regardless of the @p restore parameter.
   1147           * @par
   1148           *   If voltage scaling is supported, the restore parameter is true and the EM0
   1149           *   voltage scaling level is set higher than the EM3 level, then the EM0 level is
   1150           *   also restored.
   1151           * @par
   1152           *   On Series 2 Config 2 devices (EFRxG22), this function will also relock the
   1153           *   DPLL if the DPLL is used and @p restore is true.
   1154           *
   1155           * @param[in] restore
   1156           *   @li true - save and restore oscillators, clocks and voltage scaling, see
   1157           *   function details.
   1158           *   @li false - do not save and restore oscillators and clocks, see function
   1159           *   details.
   1160           * @par
   1161           *   The @p restore option should only be used if all clock control is done
   1162           *   via the CMU API.
   1163           ******************************************************************************/

